*** _Abort and interrupt:_
**** What abort and interrupt does ?
**** Does exception occurs in the thread when abort or interrupt is called  ? If yes what are the  name of the exception for abort and interrupt resp ?
**** Is the abort or interrupt exception once handled thrown agian ? if yes why ?
**** What happen if the thread is in suspended mode and abort or interrupt is called on the thread ?
|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Abort                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            | Interrupt                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |
|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| It is used to release a blocked thread prematurely; for instance, when ending an application.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    | It is also used to release a blocked thread prematurely; for instance, when ending an application.                                                                                                                                                                                      |
| The Abort method is also capable of ending a nonblocked thread.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                  | Interrupt only works for /blocked/ thread.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              |
| A blocked thread can also be forcibly released via its Abort method. This has an effect similar to calling Interrupt, except that a ThreadAbortException is thrown instead of a ThreadInterruptedException.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      | Interrupting a thread does not cause the thread to end, unless the /ThreadInterruptedException/ is unhandled. If Interrupt is called on a thread that's not blocked, the thread continues executing until it next blocks, at which point a ThreadInterruptedException is thrown.        |
| Furthermore, the exception will be rethrown at the end of the catch block (in an attempt to terminate the thread for good) unless Thread.ResetAbort is called within the catch block. In the interim, the thread has a ThreadState of AbortRequested.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            | It is safer to call thread when blocked by checking the ThreadState as followed . /if ((worker.ThreadState & ThreadState.WaitSleepJoin) > 0)  worker.Interrupt();/. But this is not thread-safe because of the possibility of preemption between the if statement and worker.Interrupt. |
| There are two cases, though, where you can safely use Abort. One is if you are willing to tear down a thread's application domain after it is aborted. A good example of when you might do this is in writing a unit-testing framework. Another case where you can call Abort safely is on your own thread (because you know exactly where you are). Aborting your own thread throws an unswallowable exception: one that gets rethrown after each catch block. ASP.NET does exactly this when you call Redirect.                                                                                                                |                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         |
| The big difference between Interrupt and Abort is what happens when it is called on a thread that is not blocked. Whereas Interrupt waits until the thread next blocks before doing anything, Abort throws an exception on the thread right where it is executing (unmanaged code excepted). This is a problem because .NET Framework code might be aborted  code that is not abort-safe. For example, if an abort occurs while a FileStream is being constructed, it is possible that an unmanaged file handle will remain open until the application domain ends. This rules out using Abort in almost any nontrivial context. |                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         |
| ThreadAbortException even unhandled never propogates to AppDomain.UnhandleExceptionEventHandler.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 | ThreadAbortException even unhandled never propogates to AppDomain.UnhandleExceptionEventHandler.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         |
|----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
                                                                                                   

